k58A.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Detail of “Hotel Bedroom” (1954) by Lucian Freud. Oil on canvas. 91.5 × 61 cm. Beaverbrook Art Gallery, Fredericton, Canada. Image source <a href="https://www.wikiart.org/en/lucian-freud/hotel-bedroom" target="_self">WikiArt</a> (Fair Use)</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Next to the bed stands a man. His hands are bunched up in his pockets. He looks out to the viewer with an equally estranged look — although we sense his concerns are different to hers. Something has come between them, an impasse. A moment of memory or regret has sprung up or maybe there has come a time to pause.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We don’t know exactly what’s happened, and that’s the aspect of this painting that I want to draw your attention to: its deliberate ambiguity.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*RPHY_9aRa5HvyUIM5bYYLw.jpeg"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Detail of “Hotel Bedroom” (1954) by Lucian Freud. Oil on can vas. 91.5 × 61 cm.Beaverbrook Art Gallery, Fredericton, Canada. Image source <a href="https://www.wikiart.org/en/lucian-freud/hotel-bedroom" target="_self">WikiArt</a> (Fair Use)</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">There is restlessness in the air. The artist has brilliantly juxtaposed the private space of the couple’s bed with the large window that suggests a city street. The open shutters opposite hint at the world outside the small hotel bedroom, also insinuating how the protagonists of the painting are partially absent, partially outside too.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Have you ever paused like this and felt a deep sense of comprehension that is difficult to express in words? It’s a moment of heightened perception, tinged with a touch of melancholy, where a new idea takes root and a gentle spark of insight illuminates a fresh intention.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now I want to ask: Who is the main subject of the work? Is it her or him? What is the point being made here? Whose side are we supposed to take, if any?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The fact that there are no straightforward answers to these questions is part of the work’s eloquence. We are given an intimate view into a relationship, painted in a precise linear style and with a sense of lucidity. Yet through suggestiveness and a certain enigmatic tone, the painting takes on a meaning that can only be guessed at, weighed up or debated.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The French philosopher Roland Barthes said of art: “everything is to be <em>disentangled </em>nothing <em>deciphered</em>.”</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">And just as Barthes suggests, with a painting like this we <em>range</em> over its space. Looking into this “other world”, we try to disentangle what lies before us, not solving the painting — as if it were some kind of a puzzle — but allowing it to untangle at its own pace, under its own logic.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*-jlKtMhTeBaANWpubnk58A.jpeg"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Detail of “Hotel Bedroom” (1954) by Lucian Freud. Oil on canvas. 91.5 × 61 cm. Beaverbrook Art Gallery, Fredericton, Canada. Image source <a href="https://www.wikiart.org/en/lucian-freud/hotel-bedroom" target="_self">WikiArt</a> (Fair Use)</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Freud’s painting seems to serve as a representation of isolation, highlighting the fact that the external world and the thoughts of others are, to some extent, unknown to us. Art like this reminds us — paradoxically — that we all share the same enigmatic position, being confined within our own minds and bodies.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">From this lesson of confinement, a work like this opens up the world. <mark>Art can do that. It teaches you empathy. It teaches you to slow down and ask questions. It’s worth taking your time and looking more closely, not deciphering but </mark><mark>disentangling.</mark></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">As the sculptor Auguste Rodin said:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">“Patience is also a form of action.”</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">With art, we can unwrap the experience like we’re stepping into a room we’ve never visited before. Art is a doorway to heightened awareness. We move from the familiar to the unfamiliar, from the private to the public — from the concerns of our personal lives into the wider province of humankind.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Looking at art always involves looking beyond yourself. Glimpse at a painting or a sculpture and you look into another world.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
